text: RRP marketing principles and guidance on marketing activities A. RRP marketing principles We develop and market Reduced-Risk Products1 (“RRP”) – namely Logic vaping products2 and Ploom tobacco vaporizers – to bring unique product choices to adult smokers and vapers. We understand the challenges that RRPs present global regulators; in particular their desire to increase awareness among adult smokers of the potential health benefits of fully switching to RRPs, but without unintentionally making these products an attractive proposition for minors. We are fully committed to the principle that minors should never use or access RRPs. As a responsible company, we implement business practices and trade education programs aimed at preventing minors from accessing RRPs. To further reinforce our commitment, we have considered how we should market our RRPs using modern communication methods including, for example, social media. At all times, we shall market our RRPs responsibly through strict adherence to our Core RRP Marketing Principles (“Principles”) as follows: 1. Minors should not vape and should not be able to obtain vaping products. 2. Marketing of our RRPs should target existing adult smokers and vapers. 3. Adult smokers and vapers should be adequately informed that our RRPs have the potential to reduce the risks associated with smoking but are not risk free. 4. Our RRPs are not medicinal smoking cessation products, unless they are classified as such by law in the countries in which they are sold. These Principles shall apply to all our RRP consumer and trade marketing

activities in both online and traditional retail marketing channels. 1 Reduced-Risk Products (RRP) are those, we believe, have the potential to reduce the risks associated with smoking. 2 Including both nicotine and non-nicotine containing products. 2 B. Guidance on RRP marketing activities Where permitted by applicable laws in the markets where we operate, we use marketing channels - including social media and online retail platforms - to provide accurate and relevant information about our RRP brands, our product portfolio, upcoming offers, product reviews, events and other topics of interest to our consumers. Our Principles shall apply at all times, including when laws governing the marketing of RRPs in some markets are less strict or do not exist. While sections C-E below provide more detailed guidance and non-exhaustive examples of how to apply the Principles in practice, the main themes for each of the main marketing channels we generally use, can be summarized as follows: • When using social media platforms for RRP marketing purposes: o We only establish pages or accounts on moderated sites (i.e. those where the platform owner screens or otherwise controls the content) such as Facebook, Instagram, YouTube, Twitter and, in some cases, their local or regional equivalents, e.g. VKontakte (Russia), Kakao (Korea), etc. o We use available age verification and geo-blocking tools to prevent minors from accessing our accounts. o We establish country specific accounts where the relevant platform’s tools allow (e.g. a Logic UK page on Facebook for UK users) to minimize

the possibility of content originating from one market reaching consumers in another. • When using online retail platforms for RRP sales and marketing purposes: o We age verify purchasers of our RRPs using more than a simple self-declaration of age. o We prevent bulk purchasing of our RRPs through sales monitoring procedures. o We carefully consider those online retailers to whom we supply our RRPs directly for resale, to ensure they are selling and marketing our products responsibly. • When using paid media (online and offline) for RRP marketing purposes: o We act responsibly in choosing where our advertisements are placed or physically located to ensure they target existing adult smokers and vapers. • When conducting all forms of RRP marketing: o We strictly adhere to our RRP marketing content guidelines to ensure our RRPs are marketed to existing adult smokers and vapers. 3 C. Responsible marketing to adult smokers and vapers, and age verification requirements • We deny minors access to our social media accounts by using the relevant platform’s age verification tools. This means that consumers who have not declared their dates of birth when establishing their social media profiles, as well as those consumers who have declared their dates of birth and are not of legal age to purchase vaping products, cannot access the content on our RRP social media accounts. • We apply geo-blocking tools to our social media accounts whenever they are available. This means we can exclude consumers from accessing our

social media accounts if they do not reside in the country where the relevant content was published. • We act responsibly when selecting websites and/or physical premises and locations where paid media communications will be placed. For example: o We only place paid for advertisements online on websites where it is permitted by law in the relevant market and: (a) independent data confirms that 75% or more of the users of the website are of legal age to purchase vaping products; or (b) where no such independent data is available, the website has an ‘adult’ profile (presentation, content, awareness, etc.) as determined by local market CA&C, Legal and Marketing teams. o We do not place physical paid for advertisements near schools attended by minors. (e.g. advertisements must be at least 200m away). • When making direct to consumer sales through online retail websites, we implement effective measures to verify the age of potential purchasers to ensure they are above the minimum legal age to make a purchase. Examples of these measures may include use of online age verification software, SMS code verification, accepting credit card payments only, allowing ‘collect in store’ only, implementing a mandatory ID check as part of the delivery process etc. • We implement manual internal procedures and/or software-based restrictions, aimed at preventing bulk purchases of RRPs online (e.g. a consumer buying an abnormally large quantity/value of products in one transaction or making multiple transactions over a short time period), to minimize any potential

resale of our RRPs to minors. • When supplying online retailers with RRPs for resale to consumers, we ensure they are responsible organizations and that their age verification controls for online purchases are no less onerous than our own. We conduct ongoing monitoring of any online retailers to whom we directly supply RRPs to ensure they continue applying responsible sales and marketing practices and may terminate our contracts with those who do not. 4 D. Marketing channels and content Creation and approval • We manage local social media accounts and online retail websites based on, our RRP marketing content guidelines. These provide guidance on content creation and approval. They also establish standard operating procedures to ensure good governance and consistency in our online content and communication capabilities with clearly defined roles and responsibilities. General • Our RRP marketing activities shall target existing adult smokers and vapers. For example: o We do not use flavor descriptors or imagery/text in our marketing communications that are likely to have significant appeal to minors such as cartoons, candies, ice creams/popsicles, junk foods, sodas, toys, superhero/box office movies or TV shows and their related characters. Where fruit and candy flavors are to be combined in a descriptor (e.g. Caramel Banana) or other dessert-like flavor descriptors are to be used (e.g. Maple Pecan), market CA&C and Legal teams must carefully consider the appropriateness of these on a case-by-case basis to ensure they are consistent with the Principles and not likely to have significant

appeal to minors. o We do not use @links/hashtags to themes that are likely to have significant appeal to minors or hashtags containing words that bear no relevance to our brands, brand events or vaping in general (e.g. ‘#ThrowbackThursday’, ‘#FridayFeeling’, ‘#Stylish’ ‘#Fashion’ etc.). o We do not use imagery or text in our marketing communications that may infringe the intellectual property rights of others. For the same reason, we do not use @links/hashtags to influencers/celebrities who we have no direct commercial relationships with in accordance with Section E below (e.g. #KylieJenner). o We do not depict anyone in photos/images in our marketing communications who is under 25 years old, appears to be under 25 years old, or is presented as being under 25 years old. o We do not imply that vaping contributes to sporting or athletic success, to health and fitness, to sexual, social, professional success or religious affiliation. o Where social media influencers are engaged (see section E below) to publish a paid for advertisement for our RRPs, the post must make clear that it is an advertisement by, for example, including “ADVERT”, “#adv” or other variations as may be required by local law. • Our marketing communications shall not suggest that our RRPs are medically licensed or therapeutic smoking cessation products unless authorized by law to do so in the market where the product is sold. • We shall always feature the following statement (“ELECTRONIC CIGARETTE/ HEATED TOBACCO PRODUCT – 18+ CONTAINS NICOTINE/ AND

TOBACCO - NICOTINE IS AN ADDICTIVE SUBSTANCE” – to be adapted locally), 5 in the ‘About’ section of our social media pages and in the terms and conditions of our online retail websites. The same statement shall also feature as part of the relevant images/photos that are being published in social media posts and any online paid for advertisements. Markets that are marketing zero nicotine liquids shall adapt this message accordingly, provided that such products remain firmly positioned as RRPs intended for existing adult smokers and vapers. • Product statements or claims relating to the design, composition, vaping characteristics, packaging or other aspects of our RRPs and brands must be substantiated e.g. by scientific, technical or consumer research (see RRP marketing content guidelines). • Scientific product statements or claims on Reduced Exposure (x% reduction of toxicants in vapor vs. cigarette smoke) may only be used strictly adhering to the respective Reduced-Risk Potential Messaging Guide. We do not make smoking cessation claims about our RRPs unless authorized by law in the market where the products are sold. Moderation • All our social media accounts and online retail websites must be closely monitored and moderated by the publishing market. For example, posts and comments from users on our social media accounts shall be monitored and moderated by the local market, who shall use the available channel moderation tools to apply control filters. • We ensure that all staff – be they JTI employees or from an external agency –

with the permission to publish content on our online accounts or sites, have been: o properly trained on these Principles and related guidelines and the respective escalation process in case of adverse events (see RRP marketing content guidelines); and o provided with an approved set of response actions and messages. • We do not use images of personally identifiable consumers (e.g. photography of a particular individual from a festival activation vaping our products) in our social media channels except in fully compliance with applicable laws (e.g. meaning with prior written consent in some markets). • If consumers choose to share their own social media activity relating to our RRP brands and products, it’s completely their choice. We do not ask consumers to do this and do not run competitions or promotions with consumers whereby entry or participation is dependent on them posting or sharing information about our brands on their social media profiles at our request or tagging their friends/followers in the ‘comments’ section of our social media posts. Paid media (online and offline) • Where permitted by applicable laws, we may advertise and promote our RRP brands and products through paid media. 6 • All use of paid media shall comply with applicable local laws and the Principles. For example, paid media shall only be used where 75% or more of the consumers exposed to the RRP marketing communications are of legal age to purchase vaping products as confirmed by independent data e.g. 75%+ of users

of a news corporation website and/or 75%+ readership of a magazine are known to be 18+ adults. Where no such independent data is available, the chosen media must have an ‘adult’ user profile (e.g. in terms of its presentation, content, awareness, etc.) as determined by local market CA&C, Legal and Marketing teams. For every paid media campaign, a report must be held confirming that the age verification threshold or adult user profile requirement has been met along with any other evidence to demonstrate that the campaign fully complied with the Principles. • The above-mentioned threshold (75%+) shall not apply to paid media in public spaces where it is impossible to obtain data that would verify the legal age of persons exposed to the advertisement e.g. billboards, point of sale, bus shelters, shop windows etc. Markets shall act responsibly and in accordance with the Principles when publishing these forms of marketing communications e.g. they should not place physical paid for advertisements in close proximity to schools attended by minors (advertisements must be at least 200m away). E. Use of social media influencers • We use social media influencers to raise awareness of our RRP brands and products among existing adult smokers and vapers. More specifically, we engage with suitable vaping experts (sometimes referred to as ‘micro influencers’) as well as suitable celebrities (sometimes referred to as ‘macro influencers’). • In all influencer engagements, we strictly comply with all applicable laws and the Principles. • We do not engage

with social media influencers who are under 25 years old, appear to be under 25 years old, or are presented as being under 25 years old. • We do not engage influencers that promote extreme views or positions conflicting with our strict commitment to human rights, equal opportunities, non-discrimination and diversity and inclusion, or who would otherwise not represent the spirit of the Principlessuch as actors, popstars, video gamers, sport stars etc. who are likely to have significant appeal to minors, as determined by Market CA&C and Legal teams. For clarity, ‘significant appeal’ refers to those influencers who market teams believe have a following/fanbase that predominantly comprises minors. It follows, therefore, that influencers who market teams believe have a following/fanbase that predominantly comprises adults do not have ‘significant appeal’ to minors. Market teams should take reasonable steps to assess all proposed influencer engagements, in order to reach a balanced decision on their compliance with the Principles. • We provide expert vaping influencers with free samples of our products and information about them in order that they may choose to independently rate or review them. However, we do not pay or incentivize 7 micro influencers for positive reviews or opinions on our products nor influence or edit such prior to their release. Influencer ratings or reviews shall be truly independent and reflect the personal opinions of their respective originators. • We consider third party ratings and reviews published online (including in social media) as being in the public

domain. We may seek to use these postsin our broader marketing activities as ‘earned endorsement’ for our products, with the prior consent of the originator if required by local law. • We do not invite influencers to events contingent on them posting or sharing specific information at our request on their or our social media page(s). If celebrities or ‘influencers’ share their own social media activity related to our RRP brands or products, it must be completely their choice. The same shall also apply in respect of any consumer events we run and that while these events may have equipment available such as selfie sticks, photo booths, signage with hashtags etc. we do not demand that attendees post images or footage of the event to their personal social media accounts. If they do, it is completely their choice. • As mentioned in section D, we ensure that any paid for advertisements of influencers are appropriately declared as adverts. F. Guidance owner The owner of this guidance note is Public Affairs VP. Any exception to this guidance note must be duly justified and documented by the requestor and authorized by the guidance note owner. G. Document management Contact Person Questions and feedback regarding this policy should be submitted to note owner. Review Cycle The guidance note owner, or delegate, will review and update this document at least annually or where material changes in the business environment demand it
